odex Calixtinus at Santiago de Compostela. The Spanish Civil War sent him home to American maritime history."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"He addressed a queen at the Bicentennial","body":"For the 1976 Bicentennial, Whitehill delivered a televised address on Boston’s history at the Old State House before Queen Elizabeth II. An Episcopalian Republican who kept a fifteen-thousand-volume library in a converted barn, he founded the journal The American Neptune."}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD6604","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1930,"children_ids":["HD6609","HD6610"]}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD6195","link_text":"Edgar Weld King","display_label":"a fellow library director with a library named for him"}],"slug":"walter-muir-whitehill-1905"},"HD6604":{"id":"HD6604","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"generation_from_thomas":10},"bio":{"display_name":"Jane Revere Coolidge Whitehill","first_name":"Jane Revere","last_name":"Whitehill","married_names":[],"maiden_name":"Coolidge","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781565887/6885607_07bd359d-939b-4547-9b51-feedd07f042c_psmepl.jpg"},"parents":{"father_id":"I01849","mother_id":"HD6569"},"tags":[],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I01850","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1930,"children_ids":["HD6609","HD6610"]}],"birth":{"year":1902,"date_precision":"year_only"},"death":{"year":1996,"date_precision":"year_only"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM919"},"slug":"jane-revere-whitehill-1902"},"I01849":{"id":"I01849","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"generation_from_thomas":null},"bio":{"display_name":"Julian Lowell Coolidge","first_name":"Julian Lowell","last_name":"Coolidge","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781565647/143260808_6036c123-e16b-4f3d-85ee-b4990006f259-resized_xubcab.png","bio_blurb":"Harvard mathematician; first master of Lowell House"},"birth":{"year":1873,"month":9,"day":28,"city":"Brookline","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States","date_precision":"exact"},"death":{"year":1954,"month":3,"day":5,"city":"Cambridge","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States","date_precision":"exact"},"parents":{"father_id":null,"mother_id":null},"tags":["harvard_graduate","wwi","author","mathematician"],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM549"},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["science","education"],"notable_blurb":"Harvard geometer; first master of Lowell House","primary_url":"https://legacy-www.math.harvard.edu/history/coolidge/","primary_url_label":"Harvard Mathematics"},"education":[{"institution_id":"INST002","school_name":null,"dates":"1895","type":"undergraduate","notes":"A.B. summa cum laude"},{"institution_id":null,"school_name":"Balliol College, Oxford","dates":"1897","type":"graduate","notes":"B.Sc. (Oxford’s first science degree)"},{"institution_id":null,"school_name":"University of Bonn","dates":"1904","type":"doctoral","notes":"Ph.D. under Eduard Study"}],"career":[{"role":"Teacher","organization":"Groton School","start_year":1897,"end_year":1899},{"role":"Professor of Mathematics","organization":"Harvard University","start_year":1899,"end_year":1940},{"role":"First Master","organization":"Lowell House, Harvard","start_year":1930,"end_year":1940},{"role":"Department Chairman","organization":"Harvard Mathematics","start_year":1927,"end_year":1940}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"education","header":"He taught a future president at Groton","body":"Before joining Harvard, Coolidge taught at Groton, where one of his pupils was Franklin Delano Roosevelt; the two remained friends for life. He went on to spend his whole career at Harvard, chairing its mathematics department."},{"number":2,"category":"science","header":"He held Oxford’s first science degree","body":"After Harvard, Coolidge took the very first Bachelor of Science ever awarded by Oxford, in 1897, then a doctorate at Bonn under Eduard Study. His treatises on the circle, the sphere, and non-Euclidean geometry became standards."},{"number":3,"category":"education","header":"He built Lowell House from raw brick","body":"Named the first master of Lowell House in 1930, Coolidge had to invent the residential culture of a building “new and raw from the builders’ hands.” His vision shaped Harvard’s house system for generations."},{"number":4,"category":"military","header":"A geometer who commanded two thousand men","body":"During the First World War, Coolidge served as a major and liaison officer to the French General Staff, with two thousand American men under his command in Paris. France made him a chevalier of the Legion of Honor in 1919."},{"number":5,"category":"literature","header":"In retirement he wrote mathematics’ history","body":"After retiring in 1940, Coolidge turned to the history of his field, publishing studies of geometrical methods and \"The Mathematics of Great Amateurs.\" He was a record-setting miler in his Oxford days and a lifelong oarsman."}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"HD6569","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1901,"children_ids":["HD6604","HD6605","HD6606","HD6607","HD6608"]}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"parallel_careers","related_id":"HD1263","link_text":"Prof. James Pelham Pierpont","display_label":"a fellow eminent American mathematics professor of the era"}],"slug":"julian-lowell-coolidge-1873"},"HD6569":{"id":"HD6569","classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"generation_from_thomas":9},"bio":{"display_name":"Theresa Reynolds Coolidge","first_name":"Theresa","last_name":"Coolidge","married_names":[],"maiden_name":"Reynolds","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1781565647/143260808_6036c123-e16b-4f3d-85ee-b4990006f259-resized_xubcab.png","bio_blurb":"Linguist; matriarch of a Harvard academic dynasty"},"parents":{"father_id":"HD6557","mother_id":"I01832"},"tags":["extraordinary_longevity"],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"I01849","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1901,"children_ids":["HD6604","HD6605","HD6606","HD6607","HD6608"]}],"birth":{"year":1874,"month":9,"day":26,"city":"Boston","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States","date_precision":"exact"},"death":{"year":1972,"month":1,"day":17,"city":"Cambridge","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States","date_precision":"exact"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM549"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Her marriage seeded a Harvard dynasty","body":"A linguist by training, Theresa Reynolds married the mathematician Julian Lowell Coolidge in 1901 and bore seven children. Among them were a Fogg Museum director and a daughter who married Boston’s leading cultural historian."}],"slug":"theresa-coolidge-1874"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM919","name":"Monticello Graveyard","city":"Charlottesville","county":"Albemarle County","state":"Virginia","country":"United States"},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}